1 Project Goal

The goal of this project is to understand the relationships between orange juice brands, prices, and customer purchasing patterns. We expect the lower cost orange juice to be the most important variable in the purchasing, regardless of brand, therefore we do not expect brands to matter to buyers.

2 Load packages and transform the data

# Load package
library(tidyverse) # The tidyverse package contains ggplot2, dplyr, and several other packages we will use
library(gridExtra) # use to put graphs together in the same frame
library(scales) # to get $ and , on axis in graph
library(janitor) # The janitor package contains tidyverse functions for cross-tables
library(knitr) # The knitr package contains some table formating functions
library(GGally) # The GGally package contains a custom correlation plot we will use
#Loading the Data
OJ <- read.csv("OJ_Data.csv")

#Converting factor variables into factors
OJ$STORE <- as.factor(OJ$STORE)
OJ$SpecialMM <- as.factor(OJ$SpecialMM)
OJ$SpecialCH <- as.factor(OJ$SpecialCH)

4 Base EDA Step 2: Uni-variate Graphical EDA

#Number of sales per OJ brand
grid.arrange(
  OJ %>%
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Purchase)) + 
      geom_bar() +
      theme_classic() +
      ggtitle("Citrus Hill accounts for roughly 2/3 of the orange juice purchases in this sample") +
      labs(x = 'OJ Brand', y = 'Count'), 
  OJ %>%
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = STORE, fill = Purchase)) + 
      geom_bar() +
      theme_classic() +
      ggtitle("Most of the total purchases come from store 1", sub = "store 1 and store 4 have the highest proportion of CH purchases. Stores 1-3 are relatively even") +
      labs(x = 'Store', y = 'Count'), 
  OJ %>%
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = DiscCH, y = PriceCH)) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
      geom_point() +
      theme_classic() +
      ggtitle("Discount value increases as retail price increaases for CH") +
      labs(x = 'Discount ($) CH', y = 'Price ($) CH'),
  OJ %>%
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = DiscMM, y = PriceMM)) +
      geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
      geom_point() +
      theme_classic() +
      ggtitle("Discount value stays steady regardless of MM retail price") +
      labs(x = 'Discount ($) MM', y = 'Price ($) MM'),
  ncol = 2
)

  • Citrus Hill accounts for about 2/3 of the total orange juice sales in the sample

5 Base EDA Step 3: Multi-Variate Non-Graphical EDA

5.1 Did consumers buy the cheapest retail product?

  • This column will be a binary description if the purchased brand was also the lowest priced option

    - This will help us determine how important brand name is when purchasing orange juice
OJ <- OJ %>% 
mutate(CheapestRetail = case_when(OJ$PriceMM > OJ$PriceCH ~ "CH", # MM > CH = CH is cheaper
                         OJ$PriceCH > OJ$PriceMM ~ "MM", # MM < CH = MM is cheaper
                         OJ$PriceCH == OJ$PriceMM ~ "TIE" # MM == CH = tie
))
OJ$CheapestRetail <- as.factor(OJ$CheapestRetail)
OJ %>% 
  tabyl(Purchase, CheapestRetail) %>%
  kable()
Purchase CH TIE
CH 600 53
MM 351 66
+ Comments
+ This show s that there is never a time where MinuteMaid is cheaper 
- Citrus Hill is cheaper 89% of the time, with there being a tie 11% of the time

  • When there is a tie more people prefer Minute Maid.

    • This, plus the fact that the more expensive (MM) product was purchased 351 times shows that MM is either a higher quality product, or is a better known brand name

  • Questions

  • How do the presence of discounts fit into this story?

5.2 Did consumers buy more when there was a discount?

OJ <- OJ %>% 
mutate(BestDiscount = case_when(OJ$DiscCH > OJ$DiscMM ~ "CH", # MM < CH = CH has a better discount
                         OJ$DiscMM > OJ$DiscCH ~ "MM", # MM > CH = MH has a better discount
                         OJ$DiscCH == OJ$DiscMM ~ "TIE" # MM == CH = same discount
))
OJ$BestDiscount <- as.factor(OJ$BestDiscount)
OJ %>% 
  tabyl(Purchase, BestDiscount) %>%
  adorn_totals(where = c("row", "col")) %>%
  kable()
Purchase CH MM TIE Total
CH 138 164 351 653
MM 42 158 217 417
Total 180 322 568 1070

  • Comments

  • MM and CH often are on sale for the same amount

    • when the discounts are not equal, MM is more often at a better sale

  • The presence of discounts do not seem to impact purchasing habits

  • Questions

  • While just the presence of discounts don’t impact purchasing, do the discounts cause one to be overall cheaper than the other?

5.3 Did consumers buy the cheapest overall product?

#Making columns to calculate total cost to the consumer
OJ$TotalCostCH = (OJ$PriceCH - OJ$DiscCH)
OJ$TotalCostMM = (OJ$PriceMM - OJ$DiscMM)
#calculating which total cost is cheaper
OJ <- OJ %>% 
mutate(CheapestTotal = case_when(OJ$TotalCostCH < OJ$TotalCostMM ~ "CH", # MM > CH = CH is cheaper
                         OJ$TotalCostCH > OJ$TotalCostMM ~ "MM", # MM < CH = MM is cheaper
                         OJ$TotalCostCH == OJ$TotalCostMM ~ "TIE" # MM == CH = tie
))
OJ$CheapestTotal <- as.factor(OJ$CheapestTotal)
OJ %>% 
  tabyl(Purchase, CheapestTotal) %>%
  adorn_totals(where = c("row", "col")) %>%
  kable()
Purchase CH MM TIE Total
CH 517 109 27 653
MM 239 130 48 417
Total 756 239 75 1070

7.1 Do discounts differ by store?

OJ %>%

OJ %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = DiscMM)) +

  • The patterns are very different, showing that stores do offer different discounts.

    • Store 1 and Store 4 being the biggest discounters

8 Summary

  • 1.) There seems to be two groups of shoppers

    • Those who buy the cheapest juice (most often Citrus Hill)
    • Those who value their favorite brand (most often Minute Maid)

#Professional Visual

OJ_Cost_Purch <- OJ %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Purchase, fill = CheapestTotal)) +
  geom_bar() +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_classic() + 
  ggtitle("Most Customers Prefer the Cheapest Juice", sub = "Smaller percentage have a favorite brand") +
  labs(x = 'OJ brand purchased', y = "Number of Purchases", fill = "Cheapest OJ") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("light blue", "blue", "grey"), #improve color
                    guide = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) #legend the same order as bars
